SIMPLE: relish
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relish
<hw>Rel"ish</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧l"⟦icr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Relished</conjf>
<pr>(r⟦ecr⟧l"⟦icr⟧sht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Relishing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of. <ets>relechier</ets> to
lick or taste anew; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>lechier</ets> to
lick, F. <ets>l⟦eacute⟧cher</ets>. See <er>Lecher</er>,
<er>Lick</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To taste or eat with pleasure; to
like the flavor of; to partake of with gratification; hence, to enjoy;
to be pleased with or gratified by; to experience pleasure from; <as>as,
to <ex>relish</ex> food</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now I begin to <qex>relish</qex> thy advice.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He knows how to prize his advantages, and to <qex>relish</qex> the
honors which he enjoys.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give a relish to; to cause to taste
agreeably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A savory bit that served to <qex>relish</qex> wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Relish
<hw>Rel"ish</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have a pleasing or appetizing
taste; to give gratification; to have a flavor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had I been the finder-out of this secret, it would not have
<qex>relished</qex> among my other discredits.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A theory, which, how much soever it may <qex>relish</qex> of wit
and invention, hath no foundation in nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Relish
<hw>Rel"ish</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pleasing taste;
flavor that gratifies the palate; hence, enjoyable quality; power of
pleasing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Much pleasure we have lost while we abstained⟦br⟧
From this delightful fruit, nor known till now⟦br⟧
True <qex>relish</qex>, tasting.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When liberty is gone,⟦br⟧
Life grows insipid, and has lost its <qex>relish</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Savor; quality; characteristic tinge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It preserve some <qex>relish</qex> of old writing.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A taste for; liking; appetite; fondness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>relish</qex> for whatever was excellent in arts.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have a <qex>relish</qex> for moderate praise, because it bids
fair to be judicious.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is used to impart a flavor; specifically,
something taken with food to render it more palatable or to stimulate
the appetite; a condiment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Taste; savor; flavor; appetite; zest; gusto;
liking; delight.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Relish
<hw>Rel"ish</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>The projection
or shoulder at the side of, or around, a tenon, on a tenoned
piece.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relishable</ent>⟦br⟧
